  "prompt": "How did Albert Einstein treat his disability?",
  "response": "Albert Einstein had a few health issues throughout his life, but he is most commonly noted for having difficulty with his speech as a child, which some historians have speculated may have been a form of developmental disability. Einstein also experienced various health challenges later in life, including abdominal issues and heart problems.\n\nRegarding his childhood speech difficulties, it is reported that Einstein was a late talker, which caused concern for his parents and teachers. He reportedly overcame this challenge over time and proved to be a brilliant thinker in mathematics and physics. His family and close friends supported him through his early challenges, and it is believed that they provided an encouraging environment that allowed him to thrive academically.\n\nAs he grew older, Einstein focused on his work and maintained a reflective attitude toward his health issues, often emphasizing the importance of ideas over physical limitations. He adopted a holistic approach to life, valuing intellectual pursuits, creativity, and a sense of curiosity that guided his recovery and adaptation to various challenges.\n\nOverall, Einstein's approach to his \"disability,\" as well as his other health issues, was marked by resilience and a strong emphasis on intellectual engagement, leading him to become one of the most influential scientists in history.",
